I just tried to use memorization and based on gut feeling

It seemed the most likely breakdown of families was that family 1 preferred to have groups of 2 and 3 figures. Most especially it preferred having three, so any time I saw this, I chose family 1. With 2 figures visible, I alternated randomly between 1 and 2 because I know family 2 can also have 2. Additionally, family 2 was more likely to be incomplete and have only 1 or 2 figures shown,  so whenever it was 1 figure, I almost always chose 2
Family 1 usually consists of more figures, while family 2 consists of less.
I noticed that the majority of family 1 members had more than 1 feature, and the majority of family 2 members had only 1.

Items with more figures i put into family 226

I tried to notice patterns during the example, but quickly found myself overthinking it. At that point, I decided to stop trying to "remember" anything and just pay attention to what I was looking at. When it came time to choose groups, I felt like I intuitively knew which group to place most of the objects in (even though I probably didn't do a very good job).
two circles alone was two, most right lines were two and then most upper top lines were 1

I figured that one feature on it's own was in family two, all the features together were family one, and then the combinations were mostly a guess but I assumed that if it featured the circles it might be family one.
If it had any single objects, it typically belonged to 2.  If it had the double circle with anything, it was usually 1.
